{"key":"processedPost-8624523","value":{"id":8624523,"first":8620103,"last":8624523,"when":1215870097,"utime":"07/12/08 04:41 PM","content":"Personally, I hate the cheap(under $1000) microscopes.&nbsp;  Their optics suck.&nbsp; You might look for lab auctions and the like to find a quality microscope used.&nbsp; The cheap ones only advertise the magnification, but much more important is the size and qualty of the objectives.&nbsp; I actually use my zoom microscope with a maximum magnification of 50X far more often than my light microscopes.&nbsp; <br /><br />However, for new growers getting started, a far more important big purchase is a laminar flow hood.&nbsp; A good flowhood will negate the need for a microscope until you get really geeky and want to study cell structure, look at clamp connections, and count the nuclei in a cell.&nbsp; I don't even bother trying to use my microscopes to ID contaminants.&nbsp; You can isolate away from contamination with the naked eye to clean up a culture, but you'll need agar supplies and at least a good glovebox, but a flowhood is preferred.<br />RR","title":"Re: Contamination Isolation (moved)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}